Advantages and disadvantages of the conversion of credits to Swiss francs
Two offers have already appeared on the banking market to convert the credits into Swiss francs, the main advantages being the exclusion of foreign exchange risk and the reduction of rates.
The disadvantages can come in a few years, when variable interest can lead to higher rates.
Banca Transilvania has just completed the process of converting the loans into francs granted by Volksbank, and Bancpost announced the conversion offer for its own clients.
According to the pooled data of FinZoom financial portal analysts, Bancpost offers three years of fixed interest on lei, 1.5%, the lowest on the market.
On the other hand, the offer to convert Banca Transilvania was accepted by 83% of clients with franc credits due to the second successive cuts: the balance was reduced with the value of the risk and administration fees paid by the client, then an additional reduction of 22.5% was applied to the balance in lei.
Both offers reduce the rates of their customers, compared to what they paid monthly equivalent in lei before conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42.5% and Bancpost by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the coming years.
Benefits
The main advantage of the loan in MDL in CHF is that the foreign exchange risk is eliminated, the consumer being protected from future increases in the franc, and the credit will be repaid in the currency in which he earns his salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that no revaluation of the property is made, no further guarantees are required and no further proof of income is required.
In practice, there will be no new financial and legal analysis of credit, nor will there be any additional costs as in case of refinancing.
Both banks also offer a discount at the monthly rate, compared to what customers paid before conversion, equivalent in lei.
Risks
The problem is that the rate in the first years is more of interest, and the client reimburses very little of the principal.
The Bancpost offer with very low interest rates in the first three years seems advantageous to customers.
However, it is not known how this interest will evolve after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be higher than 3.25%, so overall, and the cost reduction is lower.
A possible risk for all credits in MDL with variable interest rate is that the ROBOR index will increase significantly in the coming years (more than the Libor-CHF index).
For example, ROBOR at three months is now 1.44%, but in 2013 it reached 6%, in 2009, at more than 15%, and in a few days in 2008 it exceeded 40%!
In addition, other costs may occur, not mentioned in the original offer.
