PHE published the "reference" report last month and described it as a "complex analysis of evidence."
However, some researchers questioned the robustness of the data and pointed to links between certain experts and the tobacco industry.
An article published last month in Lancet medical magazine attacked the "extraordinarily fragile base" on which PHE founded its main conclusion.
Two other researchers who write in the BMJ questioned their claims and based them "on solid soil or on quicksand."
Martin McKee, a European public health professor at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, a professor of clinical epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, said: "A fundamental principle of public health is that policies must be based on proof of effectiveness."
They said that PHE claims that "current estimates show that e-cigarettes are 95% less harmful than smoking 'are based on a detailed analysis of evidence and models.
In reality, a single meeting attended by 12 people led to the development of a multi-criteria decision analysis model (MCDA) summarising their views on the negative effects associated with various nicotine products; the results of this meeting were briefly presented in a research paper.
McKee and Capewell claimed that one of the sponsors of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health, whose executive director was said to have received funding from British American Tobacco in the past for an independent study.
It also validated the accreditation of BAT in public health in a sustainability report, he said.
They added that one of the 12 participants in the meeting declared the funding received from an electronic cigarette manufacturer but not the funding reported to have been received from the cigarette and tobacco company, Philip Morris International.
The arguments on the basis of which panel members were selected were not provided, but some known "leaders' in the production of electronic cigarettes, some of them even declare the financing of the industry in the work.
Other participants in the meeting are not known for their expertise in tobacco control.
The head of the tobacco control section of PHE also attended the meeting.
The research work prepared by the group "strongly covers" the lack of "solid evidence of the harmful effect of most products according to most criteria," McKee and Capewell said.
However, none of these links or limitations are mentioned in the PHE report.
McKee and Capewell stated that PHE's claims that "so far there is no evidence that e-cigarettes are a factor that encourages smoking among children or non-smokers" are premature.
Professor Kevin Fenton, head of the PHE health department, says that claims in BMJ have been answered in the past.
He said: "Electronic cigarettes are significantly less harmful than smoking"
One in two people who have smoked their whole lives lose their lives because of this vice.
All evidence suggests that the risk of electronic cigarettes for health is comparatively minor, but we must continue to study the long-term effects.
PHE has a clear duty to inform the public about the information that comes out and that does not come out of evidence, especially given the high degree of public confusion about the dangers relative to tobacco.
Every year, around 80,000 people lose their lives because of a disease associated with smoking and the annual costs of the national health system due to smoking reach Â£2 billion.
By clearly expressing the current evidence - that although the use of e-cigarettes is not risk-free, they present only a fraction of the harmful effect of smoking - we are fulfilling our national duty.
