Violinist David Grimal: In Bach's era there were no world tournaments.
Beethoven, Brahms, Bartok, Enescu were working people, artists and not commercial representatives.
French violinist David Grimal is one of the great artists of our time, known not only as a soloist but also as the initiator of a less ordinary project, quite "strange," as he says himself, Les Dissonances - an orchestra formed by international singers and talented musicians, who interpret a symphonic repertoire without having a conductor, and that makes her at least a curiosity in the classical musical landscape.
Les Dissonances was at the Enescu Festival this year with two performances: a performance, on Sunday, in which the soloist was David Grimal, founder of the orchestra, and one month, when the violinist Xavier Phillips was at the forefront, the works composed by Enescu were without lack.
Both performances on the Athenaeum stage showed the audience a different way of playing classical music.
Les Dissonances appeared on the stage in 2004 as the only classical musical ensemble in which there was no conductor.
The conductor is the most important musician for musicians.
It is true, on the one hand, musicians need an education either to become soloists or to become performers in an orchestra - they speak of instrumentalists, and not of composers.
They're formed as "specialized workers."
They themselves think they need a conductor.
On the other side of the stage, for the public, all musical fetisization focuses on the conductor.
And so, business, the music industry, is marketing.
So we don't talk about music anymore.
So, if we look at this world, we have on the one hand skilled workers, which is stupid, and an audience that can't listen, but you have to watch, which is stupid again, "considers David Grimal.
The violinist tells that this change in the way he makes music came from his "musical perceptions" career as a soloist.
I was like a high-level athlete who had to do the same exercise around the world with different orchestras, to earn a lot of money and bring money to the music industry.
10 years ago, when I was about 30, I found this very depressing, because I no longer found the creativity and the human brotherhood in this system.
So, I've never found any sense in continuing on this road.
So I decided to create Les Dissonances.
This was in 2004, and at the time no one would do such a thing without a conductor: "The music world, extremely conservative, did not want such projects."
"How do you imagine marketing with a collective of musicians where there is no ego?" the artist asks.
David Grimal admits that Les Dissonaces is "a luxury," stating that none of the musicians who are part of the orchestra depend on the success of this project to live.
In 10 years of the existence of the ensemble, the absence of a conductor did not prove to be a hindrance in the musical act: "Curiously, the more complex a repertoire, the simpler it seems, because all musicians are obliged to be present in the opera and not just in the role," Grimal claims, adding that at Sunday's show "we were 74 conductors on stage."
In Grimal's opinion, the Enescu Festival is a "very brave one," precisely because it invited Les Dissonances: "An extraordinary festival, where the largest orchestras in the world are present and play three times a day, and in the midst of these orchestras you also invited this strange group."
In a temple of orchestral tradition, such as the Enescu Festival, there was the place and interest in something different, breaking barriers.
Speaking of Enescu's work, the violinist admits that he feels the Romanian music of the famous Roman composer, so he did not need a special approach when he introduced Enescu's works into his repertoire.
Grimal notes that Enescu's music is very instinctive, but this is what happens when we talk about George Enescu and Romanian music, "because there is also a George Enescu who made French music."
Grimal advocates changing the way classical musical education is done, considering that "the profession of musician, as organized today, has a sense of death" and that "the future of music represents music itself."
We don't need to tour the world five times a year if it's no use.
In Bach's era, there were no world tournaments.
Beethoven, Brahms, Bartok, Enescu were working people, who were artists and not commercial representatives.
For me, the organization of concerts, festivals, tournaments, the release of albums, they're all formidable, extraordinary, but as long as they're done in the service of music.
If not, we're in a system where creativity suffers, has no freedom.
To illustrate this phenomenon, David Grimal set the example of Romanian products before and after joining the European Union: "In Romania, before entering the EU, you had vegetables and good meat."
