At the most expected meeting in recent years, policy makers from the Federal Reserve will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide whether it is time to increase a key interest rate for the first time in almost a decade.
Above them, at the end of the central bank meeting room, a mural of the United States will be seen.
The map is meant to remind that Janet L. Yellen, President of the Fed, and his colleagues must put the nation's economic interests above all else.
The Central Bank has been given a double task by Congress: maximize the employment rate in the US and maintain price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, the Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in a decision that is too difficult to predict, which will be announced on Tuesday, and will determine whether the US economy is ready to be unleashed by the unprecedented incentive offered by the near zero short-term interest rate in force since the end of 2008.
Even though most data indicate a growing economy, recent agitation in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already cautious of adding volatility by increasing the reference rate to federal funds - even by only a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and main issues they will pursue," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think that if they were looking for an excuse not to increase the interest rate, the growing uncertainty on the world market is enough to give them arguments to wait," she said.
There is no consensus on the decision that the Fed will make, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
About half of Bloomberg's recent economists anticipated an increase in interest rate this week.
But the financial markets expect the Fed to delay, a key indicator showing that the likelihood of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a drop on the stock exchange if the Fed increased the interest rate, unless policymakers would alleviate the blow by promising that it would be a long time before the next increase.
On Tuesday, industrial media Dow Jones climbed 228,89 points, or 1.4%, up to 16.599.85.
The increase was triggered by expectations that the Fed decision-makers would maintain the stable interest rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be surprising for the Fed to increase the interest rate at this point," Lonski said.
If Fed decision-makers were to do so, "they should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in financial markets."
Other experts stated that an increase in the interest rate would calm financial markets as it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed would act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be about to increase the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step towards the slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that he expected an increase in the interest rate this year despite the liberal objections that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth was strong this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest percentage in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Wage gains showed signs of growth.
And although inflation continued not to achieve the annual target of the central bank, the Fed decision-makers claimed that a key reason was the temporary effect of sharply falling oil prices.
The economy "can cope at higher rates and needs them, given the tension in the labour market," said Ian Neudson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to deteriorate at the end of this month, after China devalued its currency.
Industrial media Dow Jones fell 16% below the top record reached in May, as investors feared the slowing down of the Chinese economy would bring down global growth.
The market has somewhat reculated this month, with the Dow index now about 10% below the peak in May.
For the Fed decision-makers, the market agitation shall be added to the complex calculation of the moment of the interest rate increase.
"Without what has happened in the financial markets and news of the weakening of the Chinese economy in recent weeks, they would be stronger at the hearing," said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and former official Fed.
Now, he predicts they'll wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about which impact will be on the US economy, and they almost have no data to base it on after the events in China," Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the major interests of the Fed, so basically it should not be taken into account in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed became the global monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been huge.
The mere allusion of then President Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could "narrow" its monetary expansion triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials are expected not only to monitor progress in other areas, but also to consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
Its decision-making process is "more art than science," Zachary Karabell, head of the global strategy department of the company managing the well-being of Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, President of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Va., said this month that "The Fed has an oversized reaction history to changes in the financial market that appear to be unrelated to economic bases."
Lacker, a member with the right to vote of the Federal Commission for the Open Market, a decision-making body, which supported the increase in the interest rate, provided the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
A financial crisis affecting Asia led the Fed to reduce the reference rate by 0.75% in three meetings, "despite the limited identification implications for the US development," Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials returned to their respective falls.
The Fed should raise the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England interest rate committee.
The last hectic period is nowhere near up to that level, he said.
"We certainly do not want to get to the point of fear of an increase in the interest rate because the markets were upset," said Posen, President Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the dual mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in this respect, I do not think it should take premature action.
