Weight loss surgery could be useful in cases of mild obese diabetes
The benefits of weight loss surgery for people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes could be maintained for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether slightly obese diabetics live longer after weight loss surgery than those undergoing nonsurgical treatments.
"It takes a long time to centralize mortality data," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, who wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss operations, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to lower the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the body's ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted in morbid obese individuals with a body mass index (BMI) 35 or higher.
The BMI, a unit of weight in relation to height, is considered normal between 18,5 and 24,9.
The BMI value of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your IMC by accessing: 1.usa.gov / 1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at the Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastrectomy in the sleeve - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes mellitus in people with mild obesity.
The average BMI in people undergoing surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received non-surgical diabetes treatments remained almost at the same level, namely 29.
Of those undergoing surgery, diabetes completely healed at 36% and partly at 28%.
In the medically treated group, by comparison, diabetes completely healed in only 1% and partly in only 2% of subjects.
In addition, the control of blood pressure, triglycerides and "bad 'LDL cholesterol were generally better in the surgical group," the authors concluded.
Researchers also monitored the blood level of Hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood glucose levels over time.
Researchers write that the optimal level of haemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean haemoglobin level A1c decreased from approximately 9% to approximately 6%.
However, in the medical group, approximately 8% was maintained.
However, this improved "glycaemic control" - reflected by improved levels of haemoglobin A1c - did not reduce the mortality rate to five years, according to chief researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year compared to the gastrectomy group in the sleeve, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), had more significant decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c (3.1% versus 2.1%) and had a higher probability of complete remission of diabetes (46.9% versus 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study conducted in people with high weight in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, Blackstone says, from the University of Arizona, the Faculty of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were approximately 29% less likely to die after 15 years compared to a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients undergoing surgery, Blackstone stated that it is an optimistic aspect for people with BMI below 35 interested in the procedure.
"This is the point where this work is critical because it states that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group," without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start to take their weight seriously when the patient's BMI reaches 27-30.
"I think we wait too long to urge people to take this issue seriously," she said.
I think that once they've accumulated these genetic changes that have shortened their bodies to obesity and diabetes, it's extremely difficult to get back to normal.
