According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Anti-Poison Centre, cases of hand detergent ingestion in children under the age of 12 reported at the Anti-Poison Centres rose from 3.266 in 2010 to 16.117 in 2014.
"Children have more frequent access to these products and, unfortunately, a percentage of them reach the emergency room," Lopez told CNN.
Lopez said that some children deliberately drink detergent and others do it to impress their friends or respond to challenges on social networks.
On YouTube can be watched movies that show teenagers drinking detergent to create cheap drinks.
It seems that teenagers have mixed detergent with mouthwash with alcohol to get a stronger drink.
Younger children can be attracted to the attractive scent of the detergent.
"A child doesn't think he's hurting her," Lopez says.
Many of the most attractive types (hand detergent) are the fragrant ones.
Strawberry, grape, orange hand detergents are the most attractive for children.
The hand detergent contains approximately 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, only a few bites can cause alcohol poisoning.
"It's very concentrated alcohol," said Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the anti-poisoning center at Kansas University Hospital, for the Fox 4 channel in Kansas City.
So we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand detergents in accessible places, and if the little ones get to them, that's a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested at school the equivalent of four sprays with strawberry-flavored hand detergent, arrived at the emergency room to receive treatment.
She had alcohol 179, twice the threshold at which an adult is considered by law under the influence of alcohol, according to Dr. Chris Ritchey, a doctor at the emergency room who treated her at the Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah was babbling and couldn't go when he arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight in a separate children's hospital to identify signs of brain damage because the girl fell and hit her head because of the alcohol, Ritchey said.
"It was scary," Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah's mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal.
Lopez advised parents and teachers to use alcohol-free wet products or napkins and to keep hand detergent out of the reach of children.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some detergents have been associated with deaths.
