The government approved, on Wednesday, the "National Immigration Strategy for 2015-2018" and the "Action Plan for the current year," documents considered to be "another stage Romania is taking as part of efforts to modernise the immigration management process on national territory," according to a press release.
The source cited shows that the strategy aims to manage immigration effectively, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and actions that reflect policies set at European level, adapted to national realities.
In view of the problems faced by the states in the immediate vicinity of Romania, measures are considered for the unitary and coherent management of situations determined by the possible emergence of an influx of illegal immigrants on Romanian territory, generated by situations of crisis of political, social, economic or military nature.
"The Romanian authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time will pay special attention to citizens from countries with migration potential or which can affect national security," the source added.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict situation in Syria, reactivating the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in areas bordering Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and increasing the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets out some general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, more rigorous controls of the legality of the residence of third-country nationals in Romania and the proper application of removal and restrictive measures, improving the national asylum system.
The national strategy also includes specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of general strategic objectives.
These include: the facilitation of access to Romania by third-party citizens who respond to employment needs, the promotion of access of third-country nationals to higher education institutions in Romania for areas and professions identified as deficient.
Regarding the 2015 Action Plan, the Government considers that this represents "a means of establishing concrete activities leading to the creation of a flexible system for halting the growing migratory phenomenon."
Romania, in a European top on the labour market
Latvia, Romania and Bulgaria recorded the greatest increase in total labour costs among the Member States of the European Union in the second quarter of the year compared to the similar period in 2014, according to data published Wednesday by the European Statistical Office (Eurostat).
The index refers to employers' staff costs.
Thus, between April and June 2015, the total cost of labour increased by 1.9% in the European Union and 1.6% in the euro area.
Romania, third place in the EU to increase labour cost
The largest increases were reported in Latvia (7.9%), Romania (7.7%), Bulgaria (6.8%), Estonia (5.5%) and Lithuania (4.3%).
The only EU countries where the hourly cost of labour fell in the second quarter of this year were Greece (minus 2.9%), Cyprus (minus 1.2%) and Italy (minus 0.4%).
The advance of labour costs in Romania between April and June 2015 is mainly due to the increase of the hourly cost of labour in industry and services, by 7.9% and 7.6% respectively.
In the construction sector, Romania registered a 5.8% advance on the hourly cost of labour.
